d Envelopes suitable tor\noarry lruj school papers now on sale\nPost Office News Store\n11 Poat Office Arcade\nMargaret John\nGALLAGHER A GALLAGHER\nGraduate and Licensed\nUndertakers and Embal mere\nMargaret L. Gallagher, only li\ncensed, graduate woman embalm\ner and undertaker in the city.\nMortuary parlors, office and res.\n571 Ftelrfiold At. Phone Bar. 1390 1\nM. J. GANNON\nFUNERAL DIRECTOR!\nAND EMBALM ER\ntli John Street\nPhone 3493\nResidence 235 Vine St.\n'Phone 1259\nI george ji!1111\nI UNDERTAKER\nAutomobile Service If Preferred:\nMORTUARY ROOMS\nlilt BROAD STREET\nB Tel. Barnum (848-2\nJOS. GORMAN\nFUNERAL DIRECTOR .1\n1849 Stratford Ave.\nTelephone Noble 1760.\nTt James St. Barnum 4850\nROURKE BOUCHER I\nUndertakers\nand Embalmers\n885 Wash. Aye. Tel. Bar. 5409.\nCalls Answered Day or Night\nBSD\nI CHARLES L. DENNIS\nFUNERAL DIRECTOR\nI Residence Barnum 2892.3. Funeral\nParlors. Ms State 6t Telephone\n(Barnum 8892-2. Calls received at\nI an7 boor of the day or night.\nL6a!i\nHENRY H.\nJOSEPH V.\n-Lieberum Heaphy-\n148 Austin St. 339 South Ave. I\nEmbalmers and Undertakers\nMORTUARY PARLORS\nS3 STATS STREET!\nTelephone Barnum IS -2\nHAWLEY WILMOTj\nI Undertakers and Erabalmars M\nI til Lafayette St., Bridgeport, Ct.\nfl George B. Hawley, lit Wash- H\nIngton Terrace; Edward H. Wll-B\nH mot.865 Clinton Av. Phone Bar. 2 SlH\nTOOT SAND CASPER\nI JtJ?S, U fUFrkf S 5 I\" CHECK DEPOSIT 7- DEPOSITED T SEvtN TIMES, i J BftCK HOME\n13 S3 I ile.i.K?PKY G I\nSAY P0Plmbros Be Willing to Be Hit for That By C. M. Payno\ni i, y o mr- 1 -iiiftMMM i \"\"ffir w w r 1\nCTf s,l w iinri innnry, nsw\nkZ&bZS r s'l TTteM AWvy \"FROM l K jf l.O I S L JLJ1 Ji-J -H,m TA A\npi 13..: M\nCLEWS' WEEKLY REVIEW\nON TRADE CONDITIONS\nFinal settlement of the controversy\nbetween Russia and Poland has not\nbeen reached, but the sipninsr of an\narmistice on the 12th day of October\ngives promise of a definite adjustment.\nAt the same time the announcement\nthat British exports are asain reach\ning a high water mark points strong\nly to continued improvement in some\nat least of the more important\nbranches o foreign business for in\nability to adjust the international bal\nance. Less hopeful indications are\nafforded by fresh propect of a serious\nBritish eoal strike. A rather better\nbusiness outlook in Germany and\nsigns of further strengthening in the\nsituation in France and Italy have\nmade the past week at least reason\nably hopeful, so far as continental af\nfairs are concerned. On the other\nhand, the development of bad bank\ning conditions in Cuba, Argentina and\nBrazil tends to offset rather better\nprospects elsewhere.\nCrop nnd Business Outlook.\nThe publication by the Department\nof Agriculture on Monday of its final\nestimates for the current year shows\nreturns uniformly higher than those\nof 1919, except in wheat, rye and a\nfew minor crops. Cotton looms up\nwell above the 1919 figure, with an\nestimate of 12,120,000 bales with the\nchances of exceeding these figures, as\nthe weather since the report was com\npiled has been ideal. The figures for\nmost of the crops are above the five\nyear average. In the case of cotton\nthe satisfactory yield is complicated\nby the current decline in price, which\nis attributed by many to insufficient\nbanking accomodation, although with\nout any warrant for the opinon. Ef\nfort to check the movement of cotton\nby violent methods, such as are be\ning attempted in some parts of the\nSouth, may produce, a bad reaction\non business and is not likely to help\nthe producer. The similar attempt\nof wheat growers to maintain wheat\nat a high level is not likely to suc\nceed, whether with or without bank\ning assistance. The truth is that the\nimmutable law of supply and demand\nis the main factor in producing low\ner prices, large supplies coming to\nthe market at a time when the de\nmand is curtailed. The recent dras\ntic marking down of quotations has\nof course rectified the situation very\nconsiderably, although readjustment\nperhaps is not yet complete either in\nagriculture or in manufacturing. In\nthe latter field the feature of the week\nwas the renewal or preaictions mai\na reduction of-steel prices would oc\ncur, probably initiated by the larg\ner independent companies. A level\nwill of course sooner or later be\nreached which will bring the producer\nand consumer together, and the signs\nare now more hopeful that this is not\nfar off.\nThe Anglo-French Maturity\nThe 15th of October proved to be\nan unusually important settlement\nperiod, adjustment of the Anglo\nFrench maturities occurring on that\ndate, while the payment of bond in\nterest on behalf of the Government\nalso fell due on the same day. So\ncompletely had the Anglo-French set\ntlement been prepared for that it\ncaused no market disturbance. Im\nports of gold equal to nearly enough\nto cover the difference between the\npurchases of exchange and redemp\ntion of bonds had practically adjusted\nthe entire balance, with the exception\nof a small remainder, which it is un\nderstood may be left abroad in the\nform of an earmarked deposit pend\ning further adjustment. The Gov\nernment's payments had been pro\nvided for by the collection of taxes\na month earlier and by the sale of\ncertificates of indebtedness. The\ncomparative ease with which the\nmarket passed through this important\nsettlement shows the underlying\nstrength of the financial and money\nsituation. Foreign credit and the at\ntitude of Americans to it has undoubt\nCasper Has a Big Bank\nedly been improved as a result of the\nsuccessful completion of these oper\nations. If it were not for the high\nrate of interest prevailing in this mar\nket a considerable development of\nforeign financing would be expected\nas an element in the near future.\nEven in existing conditions consider\nable quantities of new issues will be\nplaced here as dispatches from Europe\nare showing.\nBankins; and Money.\nExcept for temporary advances in\ncall rates no important shift in the\nmoney situation was perceptible dur\ning the past week. A slight decline\nin the Federal Reserve ratio is prob\nably attributable to stringency due to\nthe temporary tying up of the country\nand to the partial suspension of pay\nments resulting from such action.\nContinuation of these conditions may\ndepend in some measure on the early\nrelief of the \"tieup\" in staples. The\neffect of a decision made by the\nComptroller of the Treasury, to the\neffect that railroads which had failed\nto establish the amounts -due under\nthe guarantee of earnings would be\nunable to collect partial payments,\nmay subject them to the necessity of\nborrowing at relatively high rates, un\nless there should be action to reverse\nthis decision which is still possible.\nAnnouncement that receipts from in\ncome and excess profits tax this year\nrun at the rate of $5,200,000,000, have\nagain emphasized the tremendous load\nunder which the financial system of\nthe country is laboring and is appar\nently stimulating the movement for\nearly revision of the income and ex\ncess profits law possibly during the\ncoming winter session of Congress.\nExchange conditions continue to re\nflect the unsettled and doubtful con\ndition of our foreign trade and of in\nternational finartfce. The question how\nwe can effect the settlement of our\nclaims from foreign countries now\ncarried in an unfunded condition in\nour books is difficult and until it is\nanswered in some way exchange will\nDAYLIGHT SAVING\nYou don't have to lose any daylight to open\na savings account here.\nWe are open every Monday evening from\n6 until 8 o'clock for the convenience of\nour Savings Department patrons.\nCome in tonight with a nest-egg of a dollar\nor two and watch your savings grow.\nFOUR PER CENT. INTEREST ON SAVINGS\nGOVERNMENT SUPERVISION\nONE DOUiAR OPENS AN \"ACCOUNT\nAccount Till His Book\nbe subject to periodic disturbance.\nThe plans finally announced at the\nclose of the Brussels conference hold\nout no immediate propects for im\nprovement but point merely to the\nprobability of continued discussion,\nthis, however, to take place now\namong a small body of selected busi\nness men and financiers. This defers\nthe concrete proposals to grow out of\nthe conference until an evidently\nmuch later date.\nMarket Review and Outlook.\nBusiness has not been overbrisk on\nthe Exchange thfs w-eek, but the de\nmand for stocks has been fully equal\nto the supply; as a matter of fact,\nit has been demonstrated on numer\nous occasions of late that owners of\nstocks are in no mood to part with\nthem. While it is quite likely that\nthere is to be further trade reaction\nit is realized that talk of this kind,\nfor the time being at least, has been\noverdone and that the current quo\ntations for most stocks have largely\ndiscounted any further falling off in\nbusiness that may take place. The\ntime is not far off when the results of\nthe Presidential election will be\nknown, and as everything points to\nHarding's election, it is fully expected\nthat the market will receive a further\nimpetus when this becomes a certain\nty. The rails for the most part are\nheld by people who believe that event\nually their stocks will be worth more\nmoney, and as the attention of the\ngeneral public is again focused on\nthese the marketing down of a couple\nof points, would be sure to bring in\nfresh buying.\nTO HANDLE\nyour banking business with effi\nciency and dispatch is our earnest\nJames Staples &Co.\nPrivate Bankers\n189 state street\nThe Connecticut\nNational Bank\nMAIN STREET at WALL\nOpen Monday livening from 6 to 4\nIs Balanced.\nBONDS AND STOCKS\nOf proven value with estab\nlished markets.\nWILLIAM R. BULL\nSecurity Bids. Bridgeport Conn.\nPhone Bar. lis\nTHE GOVKKjNMMr\nHAS VACATED\nMore space in the Lib\nerty Bunding. Get busy\nand reserve your office in\nBridgeport's best office\nbuilding, 945 Main St.\np T tt\nSETTLE YOUR\nFUEL PROBLEM\nBY USING\nGAS Ultf\nEVERY VESSEL IS A\nThe Navy is Selling a Number of\nYACHTS, CARGO-BOATS AND TUGS\nat very low prices and on the deferred payment basis. They will fce\nsold by sealed competitive bids to be opened in the Navy Department,\nBureau of Supplies and Accounts, Washington,' D, C, on .October\n28th, 1920.\nA new catalog contains photographs of the\nvessels and complete descriptions. There are five\nwood and iron tugs, of 200 to 400 horsepower,\nprices ranging from $8,500 to J24.000. A profit\nable .business in any harbor awaits the pur\nchasers. The several yachts should find big re\nturns in the Florida-Cuba trade, prices ranging\nfrom ?4,500 to $125,000. The cruisers and gun\nboats can be converted into cargo-boats to be\nused in relieving the country's transportation re\nquirements, prices ranging from $30,000 to\n$225,000.\nPractically all of these vessels are now located\non the east coast in the larger ports. This sale\nincludes 35 vessels, 11 motor boats and motor\nvachts and the same number of steam yachts.\nThe balance is made up of tugs and several con\nvertible gunboats and cruisers that will make\nexcellent cargo-boats.\nFill in the attached coupon at once and\nBureau of Supplies and Accounts, No. 219\nBUY IT\nBy J. E. Murphy\nESTABLISHED 186B\nT. L. Watson Co\nStocks Bonds\nHeenbera N. T.\nCOR. MAIN AND\nM ONUMENTS\nand Polishing Tools\n100 STRATFORD AVENUE\nARTISTIC LASTING\nPlant Operated by Pneumatic Cutting.\nHUGHES CHAPMAN\nPhone Connection\nmany of the vessels; that is,\ninitial pament of 25 per cent.\nof accepted bid and bal\nince in six equal semi-\nannual installments.\nthree years\nbeing allowed\ncomplete pay-\nment.\nsend it in to the\nWashington, D. C.\nFROM THE NAVY\nStock Exchange.\nJOHN STREETS.\nP 27 tt.\nT. B. WARREN\nReal Estate and Insurance\n1089 Broad Street\nTel. Bar. 621\nG 6 tf\nBARGAIN\nOne regular cargo-boat of over 4,300 tons dis\nplacement the U. S. S. SURVEY, appraised at\n$370,000, is included in this sale.\nNew purchasing arrangements have been\nmade to insure the immediate sale of all these\nboats. These are the MINIMUM PRICE BASIS,\nand the DEFERRED PAYMENT BASIS.\nThe Department binds itself to accept the\nhighest bid above the minimum prie\nwhich has been set. Bids, may be made\non the deferred payment basis for\n5\nthus\nto","height":"26124","width":"20412"}}
